EAI Practicum 2.4

Understanding of the ROC curves

The goal of this exercise is to find the optimal cutoff point for classification of the defaulters and the non-defaulters. The method of choice will be the linear discriminant analysis (LDA).

The key tasks of this exercise is to:

  • Prepare data for the LDA

  • Apply the LDA onto the dataset a visualize the outcome

  • Learn how to estimate the best cut-off for classification methods automatically by researching receiver operating characteristics, ROC.

Motivation for LDA

LDA shines if there is substantial separation (aka clear water) between the two classes because the parameter estimates for the logistic regression model become unstable. Moreover, LDA is more precise when the distribution of the predictors is approximately normal in each of the classes and the sample size is small.

For the tasks below you will need libraries MASS (LDA library), ROCit (ROC curves library), pROC (library for ROC calculations), caret (library for the confusion matrix) and cutpointr (to find the optimal cutoff point). The magrittr and tidyverse library is a must-have.

Task 1: Load the credit dataset Default.csv (you will find it on the server). Think about the dataset. Does balance values fulfills all requirement for LDA? Which test would you chose to compare the distributions of balance values between defaulters and non-defaulters? How would you modify the data to be ready for using in your LDA model?

Exploratory Descriptive Analysis

Task 2: Analyze the data you want to classify? How does the defaulters and the non-defaulters groups look like? What inferences do you draw from your analysis?

As obvious from the graphs, the analyses show an enrichment of clients with 0 account balance. It is debatable, whether include them in the analysis, or omit them completely from LDA. They will impact LDA but not logistic regression because LDA uses central tendencies and standard deviation for calculations, and these are likely to be skewed by disproportionately distributed data.

LDA is sensitive for data that are not only being normally distributed, but also expects that observations in both groups have exactly the same shape of the bell curve. In other words, they have the same variance. This is not the case for default data and this would be place to acknowledge it.

Receiver operating characteristics

The default cut-off for logistic regression might not reflect the best cut-off possible. Hence, comparing the 0.5 cut-off to LDA does not make sense (although this is what most people do in their diploma theses). If you are to make the real comparison of two classification methods, best you chose the cut-offs that are the most optimal for each method. For most problems this will be something like the Younden index, which you won’t find by testing multiple cut-offs manually. You have to find it systematically, and that is what receiver operating characteristics, or ROC, do.

This is how your distributions look like on the graph. The blue line represents the optimal cut-off. But how to find it?

To find the best cut-off for one or more classification methods, you need to construct the receiver operating characteristics (ROC) curve for each method and then find the point on that curve that is most top left. The method that can make it closer to the top left corner wins.

ROC curve represents the optimal trade-off between True positive rate (TPR) and False positive rate (FPR). That is, the best trade of between identifying as many true defaulters whilst miss-classifying as few non-defaulters. It is plotted as a curve that comes from an iterative calculation of TPR and FPR, starting from a single defaulter with the highest balance, then adding the defaulter with the second highest balance to the set (containing just the first defaulters at this point) and so on.

ROCit : best for model comparison

Let’s start with ROCit, which is a good package for ROC plotting and offers some interesting data along the way. You can install the package with install.packages(“ROCit”). The ROC creation will be carried out in a single step, assuming that you have logistic regression model available as an object. If not, let’s start from the beginning.

To see the ROC curve you can use the rocit() function, which creates the ROC object that can be passed to the plot() and ksplot() function.

model_glm <- glm(default ~ balance, data = data, family = binomial)

library(ROCit)
roc <- rocit(class = model_glm$y,
             score = model_glm$fitted.values)

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(roc)
ksplot(roc)

However, to get the measure of AUC (the area under the curve) you have to perform summary()

summary(roc)
##                             
##  Method used: empirical     
##  Number of positive(s): 333 
##  Number of negative(s): 9667
##  Area under curve: 0.948

The higher number is the better. AUC provides an aggregate measure of performance across all possible classification thresholds. One way of interpreting AUC is as the probability that the model ranks a random positive example more highly than a random negative example. It is also important to remember that

  • AUC is scale-invariant. It measures how well predictions are ranked, rather than their absolute values.

  • AUC is classification-threshold-invariant. It measures the quality of the model’s predictions irrespective of what classification threshold is chosen.

The AUC measure is the best way how to tell which classification method is better. Compare the outcome of the logistic regression and the LDA using ROC curves. However, there are better libraries to mine the data than ROCit…

pROC: best for data mining

The ROCR functions are part of a huge packages intended for evaluation of clinical studies and thus its jargon is heavily influenced by that. Hence, defaulters or positives are referred to as cases and non-defaulters are controls. Don’t worry, nothing else changes and the package works just fine. Let’s create ROC with ROCR and see what utility this package adds.

library(pROC)
pROC <- pROC::roc(data$default, data$balance, algorithm = 2)

It is not particularly graphically appealing even if you plot the object. However, the wealth data are good when you want to dig in. For example, which balance values corresponds the best cut-off you can get from logistic regression? For those questions, we can use other functions packed within pROC.

pROC_results <- coords(pROC, "local maximas", ret=c("threshold", "sens", "spec",
                                          "ppv", "npv", "youden", "closest.topleft"))

cutpointr - the easiest way to get cutoff point

The cutpointr library gives you the exact optimal cutpoint along with the multitude of other measurements.

library(cutpointr)

cp <- cutpointr(data, balance, default, method = maximize_metric, metric = sum_sens_spec)
summary(cp)
plot(cp)
